  "prompt": "What is the difference between overhanging beam and cantilever beam?",
  "response": "While overhanging beams and cantilever beams are similar in some aspects, there are key differences between them:\n\nOverhanging Beam:\n1. Supported at two or more points\n2. Extends beyond at least one support\n3. Has both ends supported\n4. Load can be applied anywhere along the beam\n5. Experiences both positive and negative bending moments\n6. More common in standard structural designs\n\nCantilever Beam:\n1. Fixed/rigidly connected at only one end\n2. Extends freely from the fixed support\n3. One end is completely unsupported\n4. Load applied on the free end or along its length\n5. Primarily experiences negative bending moments\n6. Often used in specialized structural applications like balconies, bridges, and architectural features\n\nKey Similarities:\n- Both transmit loads through bending\n- Both can support external loads\n- Both experience stress and deflection\n\nExample Applications:\n- Overhanging Beam: Bridge decks, building floors\n- Cantilever Beam: Balconies, diving boards, crane arms\n\nMain distinction is the support configuration and how loads are transferred through the beam's structure.",
